"Hauglustaine D.A., Lathière J., Szopa S., Folberth G.A.","Future tropospheric ozone simulated with a climate-chemistry-biosphere model",2005,"Geophysical Research Letters","32","24",,"1","5",,,10.1029/2005GL024031,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-32644431763&partnerID=40&md5=772b51a0cdeef6193cde4e3144311563","Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l'Environnement, Bat. 712, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette CEDEX, France; School of Earth and Ocean Science (SEOS), University of Victoria, P.O. Box 1700, Victoria, BC V8W 2Y2, Canada","Hauglustaine, D.A., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l'Environnement, Bat. 712, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette CEDEX, France; Lathière, J., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l'Environnement, Bat. 712, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette CEDEX, France; Szopa, S., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l'Environnement, Bat. 712, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette CEDEX, France; Folberth, G.A., School of Earth and Ocean Science (SEOS), University of Victoria, P.O. Box 1700, Victoria, BC V8W 2Y2, Canada","A climate-chemistry model and a biogenic emission model are used to investigate the relative impact of anthropogenic and biogenic emissions of ozone precursors and anthropogenic and biogenic emissions of ozone precursors and global warming on the evolution of ozone in 2100. A warmer and wetter climate leads to enhanced ozone photochemical destruction in the lower troposphere, a more intense Brewer-Dobson circulation in the stratosphere and a lightning NOx emission increased from 5 to 7.5 Tg(N)/yr. Over Europe and the eastern US climate change locally causes surface ozone to increase because of enhanced PAN thermal decomposition and more stagnant meteorological conditions. The global and annual mean OH concentration remains quite stable and the methane lifetime is unchanged in the future. Increased biogenic emissions contribute by 30-50% to surface ozone summer formation in northern continental regions. The feedback of climate change and of biogenic emissions increases the 2000 to 2100 tropospheric ozone radiative forcing by 12%, up to a global mean value of 0.58 Wm-2. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric chemistry; Atmospheric radiation; Climate change; Computer simulation; Lightning; Ozone; Troposphere; Upper atmosphere; Anthropogenic emissions; Biogenic emission model; Biogenic emissions; Climate-chemistry model; Meteorology; anthropogenic source; ozone; radiative forcing; troposphere",,,,,,"Brasseur, G.P., Kiehl, J.T., Müller, J.-F., Schneider, T., Granier, C., Tie, X.X., Hauglustaine, D., Past and future changes in global tropospheric ozone: Impact on radiative forcing (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett., 25, pp. 3807-3810; Collins, W.J., Derwent, R.G., Garnier, B., Johnson, C.E., Sanderson, M.G., Stevenson, D.S., Effect of stratosphere-troposphere exchange on the future tropospheric ozone head (2003) J. Geophys. Res., 108 (D12), p. 8528. , doi:10.1029/2002JD002617; Cubasch, U., Projections of future climate change (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis: Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 239-287. , edited by J. T. Houghton et al., chap. 9, Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Dufresne, J.-L., Fairhead, L., Le Treut, H., Berthelot, M., Bopp, L., Ciais, P., Friedlingstein, P., Monfray, P., On the magnitude of positive feedback between future climate change and the carbon cycle (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29 (10), p. 1405. , doi:10.1029/2001GL013777; Hauglustaine, D.A., Brasseur, G.P., Evolution of tropospheric ozone under anthropogenic activities and associated radiative forcing of climate (2001) J. Geophys. Res., 106, pp. 32,337-32,360; Hauglustaine, D.A., Hourdin, F., Jourdain, L., Filiberti, M.-A., Walters, S., Lamarque, J.-F., Holland, E.A., Interactive chemistry in the Laboratoire de Meteorologie Dynamique general circulation model: Description and background tropospheric chemistry evaluation (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109. , D04314, doi:10.1029/2003JD003957; Jourdain, L., Hauglustaine, D.A., The global distribution of lightning NOx simulated on-line in a general circulation model (2001) Phys. Chem. Earth, 26, pp. 585-591; Krinner, G., Viovy, N., De Noblet, N., Ogée, J., Polcher, J., Friedlingstein, P., Ciais, P., Prentice, I.C., A dynamic global vegetation model for studies of the coupled atmosphere-biosphere system (2005) Global Biogeochem. Cyles, 19. , GB1015, doi:10.1029/2003GB002199; Lathière, J., Hauglustaine, D.A., De Noblet-Ducoudré, N., Krinner, G., Folberth, G., Past and future changes in biogenic volatile organic compound emissions simulated with a global dynamic vegetation model (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32. , L20818, doi:10.1029/2005GL024164; Nakićenović, N., (2000) Special Report on Emissions Scenarios, , Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Pickering, K.E., Wang, Y., Tao, W.-K., Price, C., Müller, J.-F., Vertical distributions of lightning NO for use in regional and global chemical transport models (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett., 103, pp. 31,203-31,216; Prather, M., Atmospheric chemistry and greenhouse gases (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis: Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 239-287. , edited by J. T. Houghton et al., chap. 4, Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Price, C., Rind, D., A simple lightning parameterization for calculating global lightning distributions (1992) J. Geophys. Res., 97, pp. 9919-9933; Rind, D., Lerner, J., McLinden, C., Changes of tracer distributions in the doubled CO2 climate (2001) J. Geophys. Res., 106, pp. 28,061-28,079; Sanderson, M.G., Jones, C.D., Collins, W.J., Johnson, C.E., Derwent, R.G., Effect of climate change on isoprene emissions and surface ozone levels (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30 (18), p. 1936. , doi:10.1029/2003GL017642; Stevenson, D.S., Johnson, C.E., Collins, W.J., Derwent, R.G., Edwards, J.M., Future estima